				\begin{document}$${\cal L} = \mathop {\sum}\limits_i {{\kern 1pt} {\mathrm{l}}(y_i,{\hat{ y}}_i)} + \mathop {\sum}\limits_{\mathrm{k}} {{\kern 1pt} {\mathrm{\Omega }}(f_{\mathrm{k}})}$$\end{document}where l is a function that measures the difference between the prediction and the target and Ω is a regularization term (complexity of the tree) to prevent overfitting. This loss function cannot be optimized using traditional optimization methods: the model is trained in an additive manner by adding a tree at a time that most improves the model (most decreases the loss) to the existing set of trees. Let xi be an i-th sample and ŷi(t-1)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
